content:
A `while`(#e7e8ea) loop is commonly used to execute a block of code while a condition is `true`(#e7e8ea).

- a `while`(#e7e8ea) loop evaluates the `condition` inside the parentheses

- if the condition is `true`(#e7e8ea), the body of the loop will execute

- the body will be executed until the `condition` evaluates to `false`(#e7e8ea)

![](https://images.code.org/a3ea872832081dd1f6b3953a0a7322fc-Screen Shot 2022-05-16 at 2.39.03 PM.png)

## Examples
### Print Numbers in a Pre-Defined Range
```
int i = 0;
int n = 4;

while(i < n) {
   System.out.println(i);
   i++;
}

```
**Output:**

0

1

2

3

## Syntax

```
while (condition) {
   // code to execute
}
```
